Big Wooly Mammoth wrote:I am still trying to figure out how I want to do a pumpkin ale this year; I like the idea of using a Belgian style ale as a base.For any that haven't brewed one before, be warned, pumpkin is a trub monster. I posted this image to g+ last night, the layers of sediment are pumpkin on the bottom and I think the yeast starter in the upper ring.A lot of people just go for a sweet and pie flavor spiced attempt, I've always thought though that the pumpkin needs to be there. I think the best pumpkin beer is probably Southern Tier's Pumking, and they definitely use pumpkin (it's listed as an ingredient on the bottle), and it's a big sweet beer so I followed that idea. I used four 5-6lb pie pumpkins, quartered each and roasted at 250 for about 2 hours with a brown sugar simple syrup drizzled over the flesh, mashed the flesh up, then added to 2 gallons of water at 170 and steeped for about 45 minutes. Then strained out through a colander, and ran the remaining flesh through my juicer (what a disaster/mess) and then added all that into my boil water. This morning after settling down I've still got a good five inches of loose sediment in the bottom of the carboy. I'll probably gelatin spike it when I transfer to secondary, and then maybe again before bottling to try and bring down the sediment and limit the loss of beer.Of course you could go full on ridiculous and just use a pumpkin as your fermenter. http://www.byo.com/stories/article/indi ... -last-call
