Hello all. I will doing my first home brew next month! Pretty stoked.I am learning from a co-worker of mine and we will be kegging. Since I live in an apartment, I am looking to invest in a mini-fridge or a keezer. I have been leaning toward creating a keezer - I have been studying this guide to check out different sizes. (I only need the GE 5.0 cu. ft)If I went down the keezer road, I would need to buy one of these as well. My question is are these freezers pretty reliable? It can't be good turning a freezer on and off all the time or is it fine? Obviously, people do it but it seems like using a controller like this would cause problems down the road. However, all the mini-fridges that I look at either are way out of my price range or suck at cooling and have terrible reviews so I am trying to see what the norm is in terms of these 2 routes.
kmeeks
Ars Tribunus Militum
et Subscriptor
Tribus: Iowa City, IA
Registered: Jan 18, 2001Posts: 2511
Posted: Wed Jan 18, 2012 1:44 pm
I have a Frigidaire freezer and Johnson digital control. I don't use it as a keg fridge anymore (though it's about to become a lager fermentation vessel), but it saw regular life in that role for 4-5 years and hasn't shown any issues with the duty cycle. I generally gave the freezer a 5-6 degree range to live in, so it didn't cycle that frequently that I noticed.One thing that I did which is a little different is built a collar for the top and then mounted the door to the collar. This image shows what I'm talking about http://www.ttbrewing.com/shimgs/right_insde.png Was pretty simple, the inside board is a 1/2x6 and then I based the rest of the measurements around the actual size of the freezer. Doing it this way allowed me to use standard shanks through the collar with the ability to return it back to a freezer if I ever wanted to (which I've done, and now going back to brewing).
DJ Immortal
Ars Tribunus Angusticlavius
Tribus: Capital District
